Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza In Croatia
---------------------------------------------
(Disease never reported before in Croatia).
A. Immediate notification report
---------------------------------
Information received on 21 Oct 2005 from Dr Mate Brstilo, Director of the
Veterinary Administration, Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry, Zagreb:
Report date: 21 Oct 2005.
Reason for immediate notification: 1st occurrence of a listed disease or
infection in a country or zone/compartment.
Precise identification of agent: [see follow-up report No. 2].
Date of first confirmation of the event: 21 Oct 2005.
Date of start of the event: 19 Oct 2005.
Clinical disease: yes.
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Details of outbreak:
First administrative division (County): Viroviticko-Podravska
Lower administrative division (municipality): Zdenci
Type of epidemiological unit: village
Name of the location: Grudnjak
Species: fau (swans)
Number of animals in the outbreak:
susceptible/ cases/ deaths/ destroyed/ slaughtered
approx. 1500 /15/ 15/ 0/ 0
About 1500 swans arrived on 19 Oct 2005 at the location of the fresh water
fish farm Grudnjak' in Zdenci municipality. 15 swans died but only 6 of
them were available for laboratory testing.
The bird deaths were notified by a farm worker to the veterinary inspector
of the county. Organ samples were taken and submitted on 19 Oct to the
Poultry Centre of the Croatian Veterinary Institute. Laboratory procedures
started as soon as the samples arrived at the laboratory. On the afternoon
of 21 Oct, avian influenza virus subtype H5 was isolated from the samples.
Diagnosis:
Laboratory where diagnostic tests were performed:
Poultry Centre of the Croatian Veterinary Institute (national reference
laboratory for diseases of poultry)
Birds examined: swans
Diagnostic tests used:
1. virus isolation in chicken embryos
Date: 21 Oct. 2005
Results: positive for virus subtype H5
2. haemagglutination inhibition test
date: 21 Oct. 2005
Results: positive
Source of outbreak or origin of infection: seasonal migration of wild birds
- swans.
Control measures
A. Undertaken:
- quarantine;
- movement control inside the country;
- screening;
- zoning;
- disinfection.
B. To be undertaken:
- control of wildlife reservoirs;
- stamping out.
Vaccination prohibited: yes.
Final report: no.
B. Follow-up report No. 1
-------------------------
Information received on 26 Oct 2005 from Dr Mate Brstilo, Director of the
Veterinary Administration, Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry, Zagreb:
End of previous report period: 21 Oct 2005 (see 1st item)
End of this report period: 24 Oct 2005.
Date of first confirmation of the event: 21 Oct 2005.
Date of start of the event: 19 Oct 2005.
Clinical disease: yes.
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Details of new outbreak:
First administrative division (County): Osjecko-baranjska
Lower administrative division (municipality): Nasice
Type of epidemiological unit: village
Name of the location:Ribnjak 1905
Date of start of the outbreak: 21 Oct 2005
Species: fau (swans)
Number of animals in the outbreak
susceptible/ cases/ deaths/ destroyed/ slaughtered
244 / -- / 15 / -- / 0
15 swans were found dead between 22 and 24 Oct 2005 on the fish farm
Ribnjak 1905, in Nasice municipality. On 22 Oct, 2 dead swans were sent to
the Poultry Centre of the Croatian Veterinary Institute. On 24 Oct 2005
they were found to be positive for avian influenza virus subtype H5.
On 23 October, in the same location, cloacal swabs were taken from 7
additional dead swans and from 4 hunted wild birds (3 shorebirds and 1
cormorant). Laboratory testing of these samples is ongoing.
Diagnosis:
Laboratory where diagnostic tests were performed:
Poultry Centre of the Croatian Veterinary
Institute (national reference laboratory for diseases of poultry)
Birds examined: swans
Diagnostic tests used:
1. virus isolation in chicken embryos
date: 24 Oct 2005
results: positive for virus subtype H5
2. haemagglutination inhibition test
date: 24 Oct 2005
Results: positive
Source of outbreak or origin of infection: seasonal migration of wild birds
- swans.
Control measures
A. Undertaken:
- quarantine;
- movement control inside the country;
- screening;
- zoning;
- disinfection of infected areas.
B. To be undertaken:
- control of wildlife reservoirs;
- stamping out.
Vaccination prohibited: yes.
Final report: no.
C. Follow-up report No. 2
-------------------------
Information received on 27 Oct 2005 from Dr Mate Brstilo, Director of the
Veterinary Administration, Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry, Zagreb:
End of previous report period: 24 Oct 2005
End of this report period: 27 Oct 2005.
Updated information about the examination of samples taken from dead swans
on the territory of Zdenci municipality:
Precise identification of agent: influenza virus type A, subtype H5N1.
Diagnosis:
Laboratories where diagnostic tests were performed:
a. Poultry Centre of the Croatian Veterinary Institute (national reference
laboratory for diseases of poultry)
Outbreak: Zdenci municipality
Birds examined: swans
Diagnostic tests used:
1. virus isolation in chicken embryos
Date: 21 Oct 2005
Results: positive for virus subtype H5
2. haemagglutination inhibition test
Date: 21 Oct 2005
Results: positive
b. VLA Weybridge (United Kingdom) (OIE Reference Laboratory)
Outbreak: Zdenci municipality
Birds examined: swans
Diagnostic tests used: PCR
Date: 26 Oct 2005
Results: positive for virus subtype H5N1 (*1)
(*1) Extract from the preliminary results report from VLA Weybridge (26 Oct
2005): "Conventional amino acid sequencing at the cleavage site of the
haemagglutinin (HA) has revealed multi basic amino acid sequences of
PQGERRRKKRGLF' which is consistent with highly pathogenic avian influenza.
Molecular phylogeny based on a short fragment (300 base pairs) of HA1
indicates that the HA gene of all the 4 samples has a 99.7 percent identity
with A/Great Black Headed Gull/Qinqhai/2/05, 99.3 percent identity with the
Turkish virus and 99.1 percent identity with the Romanian virus".
Final report: no.
