Miscellaneous: Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza Virus Detected In An
Import Quarantine Unit In The United Kingdom
------------------------------------------------
Information received on 24 Oct 2005 from Dr Debby Reynolds, Director
General for Animal Health and Welfare, Department for Environment, Food and
Rural Affairs (DEFRA), London:
Report date: 24 Oct 2005.
Highly pathogenic avian influenza serotype H5N1 has been detected in a
quarantine establishment in Essex, England.
The quarantine is approved under European Commission Decision 2000/666/EC
and consists of a single biosecure unit.
2 consignments of birds were sharing the unit. The 1st was a consignment of
148 psittacines imported from Surinam on 16 Sep 2005. The 2nd was a mixed
consignment of non-psittacines imported from Taipei China on 26 Sep 2005.
The birds were housed in a number of separate but adjacent pens in the same
airspace.
Sentinel chickens were also present in the unit during the quarantine period.
There were a number of deaths during the quarantine period. 2 carcasses
from the Surinam
consignment were examined post-mortem; virological tests at the VLA
Weybridge (Veterinary Laboratories Agency, United Kingdom; European Union
Reference Laboratory) were negative.
2 further dead birds were submitted for examination on 14 Oct. A pooled
sample was submitted for virology. On 21 Oct a virus was found of serotype
H5. On 23 Oct this was
confirmed as H5N1. The closest match is a strain identified in ducks in the
People's Republic of China earlier this year. It is not so similar to the
strains from Romania and Turkey. It is not a strain that the VLA has seen
before.
Our working hypothesis is that an infection in the birds from Surinam is
likely to have arisen in the quarantine system, most likely in the facility
in Essex where the Surinam birds shared airspace with the birds from Taipei
China.
All the remaining birds in the quarantine unit were humanely killed on 21
Oct 2005 and the carcasses sent for incineration. The quarantine building
is being cleansed and disinfected.
Movements on and off the premises have been investigated and no evidence of
disease spread has been found. No live birds were removed from the
quarantine unit during the quarantine period.
Further investigations are continuing, including virological examination of
birds which died or were killed, including the sentinel chickens.
This incident occurred in an officially approved quarantine unit and there
is no indication that biosecurity has been breached. The United Kingdom
therefore remains free from avian influenza.
--
